01:51.987 --> 01:53.988
<i>It was 1947,</i>

01:54.406 --> 01:56.949
<i>two years after the war,
when I began my journey</i>

01:57.034 --> 02:00.203
<i>to what my father called
the "Sodom of the north,"</i>

02:00.287 --> 02:01.537
<i>New York.</i>

02:02.581 --> 02:03.956
<i>Call me Stingo,</i>

02:04.041 --> 02:06.793
<i>which was the nickname
I was known by in those days,</i>

02:06.877 --> 02:09.211
<i>if I was called anything at all.</i>

02:10.255 --> 02:13.424
<i>I had barely saved enough money
to write my novel,</i>

02:14.259 --> 02:18.554
<i>for I wanted beyond hope or dreaming
to be a writer.</i>

02:19.014 --> 02:21.641
<i>But my spirit had remained landlocked,</i>

02:22.142 --> 02:25.478
<i>unacquainted with love
and a stranger to death.</i>

02:28.482 --> 02:29.482
<i>Even back then,</i>

02:29.566 --> 02:32.693
<i>cheap apartments were hard to find
in Manhattan.</i>

02:34.696 --> 02:37.448
<i>And so began my voyage of discovery</i>

02:38.450 --> 02:40.910
<i>in a place as strange as Brooklyn.</i>

03:04.935 --> 03:06.143
I know.

03:06.603 --> 03:10.064
You're thinking about the pink.
Everybody does.

03:10.941 --> 03:14.318
See, my late husband Saul,
he got his bargain.

03:14.778 --> 03:19.574
Hundreds and hundreds of gallons
of this navy surplus paint.

03:20.033 --> 03:23.911
See, I guess they didn't have any use for pink
on those boats, huh?

03:26.665 --> 03:28.457
Okay, I'll take it.

04:44.284 --> 04:45.493
Oh, I love you!

05:15.107 --> 05:17.024
Don't go! Don't go!

05:17.150 --> 05:19.068
- I'm out of here. Don't!
- No!

05:27.828 --> 05:29.578
We need each other.

05:35.669 --> 05:38.004
I told you to leave me alone.

05:38.088 --> 05:40.339
Stay away from me.
Get out of my way.

05:40.424 --> 05:41.924
No, no, don't!

05:42.843 --> 05:45.177
- I'm not lying, you know!
- You're lying.

05:45.345 --> 05:46.887
- I'm not!
- You're lying.

05:47.222 --> 05:50.391
Please, don't go!
Don't go away from me, please!

05:50.600 --> 05:52.518
You know we need each other, Nathan,
you know this.

05:52.602 --> 05:53.644
We need each other.

05:53.729 --> 05:54.687
- Me need you?
- Yes...

05:54.771 --> 05:56.439
Let me tell you something.

05:56.523 --> 06:00.609
I need you like any goddamned
insufferable disease I can name!

06:00.694 --> 06:03.612
I need you like a case of anthrax,
hear me?

06:03.905 --> 06:05.489
Like trichinosis.

06:05.574 --> 06:10.536
I need you like a biliary calculus,
pellagra, encephalitis.

06:10.620 --> 06:12.538
Bright's disease, for Christ's sake!

06:12.622 --> 06:14.498
Carcinoma of the brain!

06:14.875 --> 06:17.251
I need you like death.

06:17.544 --> 06:19.336
Hear me? Like death.

06:19.421 --> 06:20.796
No, Nathan.

06:21.757 --> 06:23.758
Go back to Krakow, baby.

06:24.301 --> 06:25.968
Back to Krakow!

06:31.957 --> 06:33.642
Well, good evening.

06:34.269 --> 06:35.895
Did you have a good time?

06:35.979 --> 06:37.563
I mean, did you enjoy our little show?

06:37.647 --> 06:40.608
Do you get off
on your little bit of eavesdropping?

06:40.692 --> 06:43.027
You just... My door was open.
I just wondered what was going on.

06:43.820 --> 06:46.614
Your door was open?
You wondered what was going on?

06:46.698 --> 06:51.327
Well, shut my mouth if it isn't
our new literate figure from the South.

06:52.120 --> 06:55.539
Too bad I won't be around
for a little lively conversation.

06:55.749 --> 06:59.168
We would've had a great time,
you and I, shooting the shit.

06:59.252 --> 07:01.587
We could've talked about sports.

07:02.172 --> 07:03.756
Southern sports like

07:03.840 --> 07:07.676
lynching niggers, or "coons,"
I think you all call them down there.

07:09.513 --> 07:12.389
So long, cracker.
See you in another life.

07:16.228 --> 07:17.520
You okay?

07:18.438 --> 07:19.522
Yes.

07:21.066 --> 07:22.191
Yeah.

07:30.291 --> 07:31.534
I'm very sorry.

07:36.665 --> 07:38.374
That's not the way

07:40.043 --> 07:41.919
he really is, you know?

07:43.046 --> 07:45.339
No, don't apologize, all right?

07:45.966 --> 07:48.467
I live downstairs here.
If there's anything you want...

07:48.552 --> 07:49.927
Thank you.

07:53.390 --> 07:55.057
You're very kind.

07:55.433 --> 07:56.976
Anyway, I'm downstairs here.

07:57.060 --> 07:58.519
No, I'm all right.

08:04.818 --> 08:06.235
I'm Stingo.

08:11.199 --> 08:13.450
Please forgive us.

08:18.623 --> 08:22.334
Sixty cents. Anytime he raises 50 cents.

08:22.719 --> 08:23.711
Sixty...

08:27.257 --> 08:28.382
Yeah?

08:47.927 --> 08:50.279
We had invited you to dinner.

08:51.114 --> 08:53.282
That's very thoughtful of you.

08:53.450 --> 08:57.912
Uh, listen, I very often work at night
and type at night.

08:58.663 --> 09:00.998
But if it's going to bother you,
I don't want to...

09:01.082 --> 09:02.082
Oh, no!

09:02.167 --> 09:03.250
When I was a little girl,

09:03.335 --> 09:08.255
my father type and I go to sleep
to that sound.

09:09.799 --> 09:11.592
It'll make me feel...

09:13.303 --> 09:14.929
God, how do you say that?

09:15.013 --> 09:16.972
Secure. Secure.

09:18.642 --> 09:20.059
Your father was a writer?

09:20.143 --> 09:21.852
No, my father was...

09:21.937 --> 09:24.104
My father was professor of law.

09:24.189 --> 09:25.814
He wrote articles

09:26.149 --> 09:29.652
warning Polish people of the Nazi threat

09:30.612 --> 09:34.615
and trying to get help for those Jews
that was persecuted, so.

09:35.700 --> 09:39.370
Yeah, that sound of typing
will make me think of my father

09:40.705 --> 09:42.498
and of his goodness.

09:43.416 --> 09:45.000
You wouldn't want to come in,
would you?

09:45.835 --> 09:47.544
Maybe some other time.

09:47.629 --> 09:49.588
So, if you'll forgive me.

09:51.007 --> 09:52.675
- Good night.
- Yeah.

09:54.010 --> 09:55.094
Stinko, yeah?

09:55.971 --> 09:57.388
Stingo.

09:57.472 --> 09:58.848
Stingo, yes!

09:59.849 --> 10:01.809
I never hear that name.

10:02.644 --> 10:03.811
There's no "K" in there, though.

10:03.895 --> 10:04.895
I got it.

10:04.980 --> 10:06.522
Just a "G."

10:07.148 --> 10:08.274
Yeah, it's nice!

10:09.442 --> 10:13.153
It's a friendly, you know, happy sound.

10:13.446 --> 10:14.530
I like it.

12:09.011 --> 12:10.437
Oh, Nathan!

12:13.566 --> 12:14.775
Oh, Nathan.

12:21.324 --> 12:22.825
Oh, God!

12:31.835 --> 12:35.212
Don't you see, Sophie?
We are dying.

12:41.553 --> 12:45.264
Rise and shine, honey child.
Stir them lazy bones.

12:45.849 --> 12:48.308
The grits on the griddle,
the corn's on the pone.

12:48.643 --> 12:50.978
Old Ponkers plan to hitch up
the coach and four.

12:51.354 --> 12:55.023
You're going to have a picnic out
and down by the seashore.

12:55.525 --> 12:56.984
Good morning, Stingo.

12:57.068 --> 12:58.068
Good morning.

12:59.112 --> 13:02.406
We wanted to make friends

13:02.490 --> 13:05.200
and to take you out
on this beautiful summer day!

13:05.285 --> 13:07.828
We want you to come up
and have breakfast with us.

13:07.912 --> 13:09.204
- And then...
- Yes.

13:09.330 --> 13:10.456
Coney Island.

13:10.540 --> 13:12.124
Coney Island! Oh, boy!

13:14.002 --> 13:15.919
Sorry about last night.

13:16.546 --> 13:17.713
Yeah.

13:48.828 --> 13:51.955
I know what you're thinking.
"These people are strange."

13:52.040 --> 13:55.959
On Sundays, we like to dress up
a little differently and go out.

13:58.588 --> 14:00.088
- Okay.
- Okay?

14:00.298 --> 14:01.673
I knew you'd understand!

14:01.925 --> 14:05.093
You see, everybody out there
dresses the same.

14:05.428 --> 14:07.137
Look at those poor,
pathetic people out there.

14:07.222 --> 14:08.722
Look at them. Drones.

14:08.848 --> 14:11.600
All walking down the street,
all look alike,

14:11.684 --> 14:14.436
all wearing the same drab, boring uniform.

14:14.771 --> 14:16.230
You're boring!

14:16.564 --> 14:17.564
Morning!

14:19.275 --> 14:22.027
Now, this one. Look at this.
God's gift!

14:22.570 --> 14:24.112
Give me a kiss.

14:24.572 --> 14:25.614
One kiss. Please.

14:25.698 --> 14:28.867
All right, one kiss.
That's all you deserve.

14:28.952 --> 14:30.035
One more. I need one more.

14:30.119 --> 14:31.078
No.

14:31.162 --> 14:33.038
- I have to have one more.
- Nathan...

14:33.122 --> 14:35.290
Can't keep my hands off of you.

14:35.500 --> 14:37.793
This is... No, Nathan Landau!

14:38.127 --> 14:39.262
What do you think of that, Stingo?

14:40.046 --> 14:42.631
Here I am, a nice Jewish boy,

14:43.758 --> 14:45.300
pushing 30.

14:45.468 --> 14:47.803
I fall crazy in love with a Polish shiksa.

14:48.388 --> 14:49.888
What is that? What is a "shiksa"?

14:49.973 --> 14:54.309
A shiksa is a goy girl.
A lady of the Gentile persuasion.

14:56.104 --> 14:57.279
She's a...

14:57.814 --> 15:01.316
All right. I just assumed that she was...

15:02.110 --> 15:03.902
- She was Jewish?
- Yeah.

15:03.987 --> 15:05.153
Jewish?

15:05.321 --> 15:08.824
No, no, no.
No, our Sophie is Catholic.

15:10.702 --> 15:14.288
Yeah. Well, it's okay,
but I'm not anymore Catholic, so.

15:14.831 --> 15:16.373
Well, Catholic-ish.

15:17.834 --> 15:20.168
When I first met this one here,

15:20.503 --> 15:23.255
she was a rag and a bone
and a hank of hair.

15:23.715 --> 15:25.340
And that was a whole year-and-a-half

15:25.425 --> 15:28.260
after the Russians had liberated
the camp she was in.

15:28.344 --> 15:32.514
Yeah, it looked like something
that scares the birds.

15:32.724 --> 15:35.851
What is that? Scarecrow.

15:37.253 --> 15:38.645
I had "scurbut."

15:38.730 --> 15:41.398
No, no, no! She means scurvy.

15:41.691 --> 15:44.401
And typhus and anemia and scarlet fever.

15:44.485 --> 15:47.112
It was a fucking miracle
that she emerged from that camp alive.

15:47.196 --> 15:48.280
Right.

15:48.364 --> 15:52.034
I mean, I thought that I had leukemia.

15:54.579 --> 15:56.455
I thought I was dying.

15:57.206 --> 16:00.834
But it was Nathan that see
that it was only anemia.

16:01.544 --> 16:02.502
Are you a doctor?

16:02.587 --> 16:03.587
No, no.

16:03.671 --> 16:05.631
That's my brother's domain.

16:05.715 --> 16:06.673
But I'm a biologist.

16:06.758 --> 16:07.758
Yeah!

16:08.301 --> 16:10.385
- I graduated in science from Harvard.
- Harvard.

16:10.470 --> 16:11.521
And he...

16:12.805 --> 16:17.267
MA in Developmental and Cellular Biology.

16:18.561 --> 16:19.645
I do research now.

16:19.729 --> 16:20.687
He works at Pfizer.

16:20.772 --> 16:23.815
Pfizer, it's a big pharmaceutical house
here in Brooklyn.

16:23.900 --> 16:27.069
Anyway, I took her to this friend
of my brother's,

16:27.153 --> 16:29.488
a doctor who teaches up
at Columbia Presbyterian.

16:29.614 --> 16:30.697
Yeah.

16:30.782 --> 16:32.866
He confirmed my diagnosis.

16:33.076 --> 16:35.327
And we put the little sweetie here

16:35.411 --> 16:37.913
on massive doses of ferrous sulfate

16:38.915 --> 16:41.416
and she began to bloom like a rose.

16:42.794 --> 16:44.010
A rose.

16:44.962 --> 16:46.213
A rose.

16:48.007 --> 16:50.050
A beautiful fucking rose.

16:53.429 --> 16:55.097
You're something.

16:55.598 --> 16:58.725
Thank you for making me
to bloom like a rose.

17:08.611 --> 17:11.029
Not "to bloom," just "bloom."

17:11.280 --> 17:12.698
She's so good.
It's about time she was perfect.

17:12.781 --> 17:16.117
"To bloom." So what?
I mean, this is a ridiculous language!

17:16.202 --> 17:17.911
There's too many words!

17:17.994 --> 17:22.207
The word for "velocity," okay,
there's "fast, quick, rapid,"

17:22.290 --> 17:24.126
and they all mean the same thing.

17:24.210 --> 17:25.377
Swift, speedy.

17:25.461 --> 17:26.586
Hasty.

17:26.963 --> 17:28.422
- Fleet.
- Brisk.

17:28.756 --> 17:30.716
- Expeditious.
- Accelerated.

17:30.800 --> 17:32.092
Winged.

17:32.552 --> 17:34.803
No, no! Stop it!

17:35.722 --> 17:37.305
It's ridiculous!

17:37.890 --> 17:41.560
In French, it's so easy.
You say <i>vite.</i>

17:41.644 --> 17:44.855
Or in Polish, <i>szybko,</i>
and in Russian, <i>bystro.</i>

17:44.939 --> 17:48.525
It's only in the English it's so complicated!

17:48.609 --> 17:50.026
How many languages do you know?

17:50.111 --> 17:52.738
Well, my father was a linguist,
so I mean, I...

17:52.822 --> 17:56.491
He teach me German, French, Russian, Hungarian,

17:56.576 --> 17:58.410
the Slavic languages.

17:59.162 --> 18:02.664
So, what language I am butchering now?

18:03.583 --> 18:04.750
English!

18:04.959 --> 18:07.961
I bet your father was
a very interesting man.

18:12.300 --> 18:14.301
Yeah, my father was

18:16.345 --> 18:17.971
a civilized man.

18:22.435 --> 18:25.187
That's the word, yeah? "Civilized"?

18:25.563 --> 18:27.439
- Very good word.
- Yeah?

18:27.523 --> 18:31.276
My father was a civilized man
living in a non-civilized time.

18:31.861 --> 18:34.780
The civilized, they was the first to die.

18:37.200 --> 18:39.117
Do you play the piano?

18:39.410 --> 18:42.037
No. I used to play, but I...

18:45.750 --> 18:47.501
I no longer play.

18:49.879 --> 18:51.546
I don't anymore.

18:52.715 --> 18:55.175
My mother was a beautiful pianist.

19:00.890 --> 19:05.060
Nathan surprised me
with that piano on my birthday!

19:31.462 --> 19:33.171
I love that piece.

19:48.729 --> 19:50.272
When I was a little girl,

19:51.566 --> 19:53.650
I remember, I'd lay in bed

19:53.734 --> 19:57.404
and I'd hear my mother downstairs
playing the piano,

19:59.615 --> 20:02.367
and the sound of my father's typewriter.

20:05.204 --> 20:10.500
I think no child has a more
wonderful father and mother.

20:16.632 --> 20:18.550
And a more beautiful life.

20:36.152 --> 20:37.819
<i>Swanee,</i> you know that song, right?

20:53.878 --> 20:55.170
Stingo, hit it!

21:59.902 --> 22:02.404
Oh, God!

22:02.571 --> 22:05.073
<i>Suddenly, I shivered violently.</i>

22:06.492 --> 22:09.619
<i>I remembered Nathan's voice
that night before.</i>

22:11.247 --> 22:14.833
<i>"Don't you see, Sophie?
We are dying."</i>

22:16.043 --> 22:18.545
<i>I longed desperately to escape,</i>

22:19.255 --> 22:21.423
<i>to pack my bags and flee.</i>

22:22.216 --> 22:23.758
<i>But I did not.</i>

22:25.469 --> 22:27.679
<i>I stayed at Yetta Zimmerman's,</i>

22:27.763 --> 22:32.392
<i>and thus I helped fulfill Sophie's prophecy
about the three of us.</i>

22:32.476 --> 22:34.978
<i>We became the best of friends.</i>

24:11.200 --> 24:16.246
Here is an example of how emotionally
evocative English can be.

24:16.330 --> 24:19.624
<i>Sophie loved to tell
how Nathan saved her life.</i>

24:20.501 --> 24:24.129
<i>Their meeting was, for her, a miracle.</i>

24:24.213 --> 24:26.965
"Because I could not stop for Death,

24:27.216 --> 24:30.135
"he kindly stopped for me.

24:30.219 --> 24:34.013
"The carriage held but just ourselves
and Immortality."

24:35.391 --> 24:37.267
Rhymes, rhymes.

24:37.351 --> 24:39.102
It's not hard enough
to understand the language.

24:40.271 --> 24:43.356
Just everyday life talk.
He has to read us rhymes!

24:43.440 --> 24:47.694
...what the beauty of the language can be
when written by artists.

24:48.737 --> 24:51.865
I look forward to seeing you all next week.
And now remember,

24:53.033 --> 24:55.160
you must not get discouraged.

24:55.744 --> 24:57.203
You'll see.

24:57.288 --> 25:00.623
One morning, you'll wake up
and find you've been dreaming in English.

25:02.084 --> 25:04.878
Excuse me.
Who did he say wrote that poem?

25:04.962 --> 25:06.671
Dickens.

25:06.755 --> 25:08.423
Emily Dickens.

25:08.507 --> 25:09.966
Thank you.

25:14.805 --> 25:19.267
All I want is that we should be able
to make living...

25:22.771 --> 25:25.648
Are you all right, Miss Zawistowska?

25:32.281 --> 25:33.615
Yes.

25:35.659 --> 25:38.286
Thank you, I'm very fine.

25:38.370 --> 25:39.787
I'm a little tired.

25:39.872 --> 25:44.792
I noticed that you've been looking, well,
a little delicate lately.

25:46.378 --> 25:47.754
I hope I'm not being too personal.

25:47.838 --> 25:49.589
No! No, I...

25:51.217 --> 25:53.676
Could you help me with that?

26:01.518 --> 26:02.977
Thank you.

26:04.730 --> 26:06.564
Thank you for your

26:08.275 --> 26:09.442
concern.

26:17.910 --> 26:19.369
Goodbye.

26:43.960 --> 26:46.938
Excuse me, sir. Could you tell me what...

26:49.483 --> 26:53.361
Where would be that listing
in catalog file

26:54.280 --> 26:55.530
for

26:57.700 --> 27:01.077
19th century American poet,

27:03.497 --> 27:05.581
Emily Dickens, please?

27:05.791 --> 27:07.792
In the catalog room on the left.

27:09.503 --> 27:11.379
But you won't find
any such listing.

27:13.257 --> 27:15.174
Oh, I won't find that listing?

27:16.844 --> 27:20.221
Why wouldn't I find it?

27:23.392 --> 27:26.477
Charles Dickens is an English writer.

27:27.396 --> 27:29.689
There is no American poet
by the name of Dickens.

27:34.320 --> 27:38.531
I'm sorry. No, that is,
I'm sure, American poet.

27:41.035 --> 27:42.035
Emily Dickens.

27:42.119 --> 27:43.244
Listen!

27:43.996 --> 27:45.747
- D-I...
- I told you!

27:46.749 --> 27:47.999
There's no such person.

27:48.459 --> 27:50.418
- Do you want me to draw you a picture?
- No.

27:50.502 --> 27:53.504
- I'm telling you, you hear me?
- All right.

28:09.980 --> 28:12.273
It's all right, it's all right.

28:18.781 --> 28:20.365
Just lie still.

28:21.492 --> 28:22.992
Let the doctor take care of everything.

28:25.996 --> 28:27.497
You're so beautiful.

28:28.957 --> 28:32.126
Yes! How did you get
to be so beautiful?

28:36.465 --> 28:38.966
I think I'm going to die.

28:42.096 --> 28:44.138
No, no, no.

28:44.223 --> 28:47.266
No, your pulse...

28:47.851 --> 28:51.270
Your pulse is fine. It's steady.

28:52.481 --> 28:54.524
You're going to live to be 100.

29:57.838 --> 29:59.922
Why I am so tired?

30:01.633 --> 30:06.554
The doctor thinks you need to get some color
into that beautiful white skin of yours.

30:06.638 --> 30:09.849
I'm going to take you
to see my brother.

30:09.933 --> 30:12.518
He is the best doctor going.

30:15.230 --> 30:16.397
No, but you...

30:16.482 --> 30:17.607
Oh, you thought I was a doctor?

30:17.941 --> 30:20.359
No. No, I'm a biologist.

30:21.528 --> 30:22.778
Have you been eating properly lately?

30:23.071 --> 30:26.032
Yes! Oh, yes! I am...

30:27.534 --> 30:31.746
I am six months in here, in US and...

30:34.041 --> 30:38.753
So I eat more good now
than in my life.

30:39.922 --> 30:43.049
You could've fallen behind with iron
and never had a chance to catch up.

30:44.259 --> 30:48.262
Look, I'm going to go now
but may I come back later?

30:48.388 --> 30:50.723
No, don't answer that.
I'll be back.

30:56.146 --> 30:57.605
Okay?

31:00.067 --> 31:01.567
Yeah, okay.

31:27.302 --> 31:29.011
How long you have been there?

31:29.972 --> 31:32.848
Just long enough to get dinner started.

31:34.309 --> 31:36.143
You look much better.

